<p style="line-height:24px;"><span style="font-size:48px;line-height:12px;">I</span>&#8217;m slowly being reintroduced to my pre-pandemic life, accepting invitations to the types of events I went to all the time before the coronavirus made society sick.</p>

<p>The big outing this week was to the Gio Ponti-designed building at the Denver Art Museum, renovated and renamed, and the collections rehung to better place art in context. One of the big changes there was completion of the 7th floor as a home for the (really fantastic) Western art collection and a place to catch expansive views from new decks and slivers of the city through peek-a-boo windows that I barely remember from the before time.</p>

<p>It was glorious to watch the sun begin to lean toward the foothills, shining a slow-moving beam of light over Table Mountain to the west as the afternoon shade settled on the low-slung neighborhoods at the feet of the museum.</p>

<p>Not so glorious? The illumination of the afternoon haze low on the horizon. The more things change, the more they stay the same. But as we learn from the reporting of <strong>Michael Booth </strong>and <strong>Kevin Simpson</strong> today, the Colorado Department of Transportation is stepping up to help make a dent in the pollution caused by motor vehicles. Wait. What?</p>

