<h2><strong>&gt;&gt; What is VMT and how will it change how we&#8217;ll drive?</strong></h2>

<p>The state agency that&#8217;s poured roadways for automobiles for 100 years is laying a new path to becoming a climate warrior for Colorado.</p>

<p>And if conservation groups get their way, you&#8217;re going to hear a lot more about your vehicle miles traveled, or VMT, in coming years and how your government needs you to cut back.</p>

<p>If business and employer groups get their way, VMT will remain an obscure topic for sleepy regional council retreats, and not the primary measure of whether Colorado has trimmed greenhouse gases.</p>

<p>VMT is what it sounds like: How many miles did all the vehicles on Colorado&#8217;s roads drive on a given day, or in a given year? When nearly all those vehicles are powered by fossil fuels, more people and more miles mean more greenhouse gas emissions.</p>

<p>Conservation groups don&#8217;t want to see massive new interstate lanes or state highway interchanges until planners can prove they will cut VMT. This can be done by adding transit lanes and funding a big bus network, for example. Or by requiring county planners to plot offices and homes and grocery stores within walking distance of each other.</p>

<p>State government tried a modest effort to get big employers to start contributing to VMT cuts over the summer. The Air Quality Control Commission wanted employers of 100 people or more to survey how their workers got to the job and where they drove for work, then start cutting back from that number by encouraging carpooling, offering bus passes or letting people work from home. Business groups attacked the plan as a bureaucratic and logistical nightmare, and celebrated when state air pollution staff withdrew the idea.</p>

<p>The Colorado Energy Office, meanwhile, hopes much of the challenge can be accomplished by electrifying everything. VMT doesn&#8217;t matter so much if the vehicles are powered by cleanly generated electricity or hydrogen. So, the energy office says, focus on trading fossil fuel trucks and cars for electric, and build the charging network to support them. Call it Clean VMT.</p>

<p>Exactly how big a problem are we talking about? <a target="_blank"  href="https://drcog.org/sites/default/files/resources/2019_annual_congestion_report.pdf">Metro Denver drivers tallied 84.3 million miles a day before the pandemic</a>. Two million more people will likely live in Colorado by 2040, most of them driving in metro Denver. And transportation emissions make up one of the largest — and so far untouched — sectors of greenhouse gases.</p>

  <p>Read on to learn how the Colorado Department of Transportation is remaking itself to help the state reach the ambitious goal of cutting emissions by 26%.</p><p>&gt;&gt; <strong>Can a climate-conscious CDOT build new roads and cut greenhouse gases at the same time? </strong>&gt;&gt; <strong><a href="https://coloradosun.com/2021/11/21/climate-conscious-cdot/" target="_blank">STORY</a></strong></p>

