</mj-text><mj-image src="https://lede-admin.coloradosun.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/15/2021/11/IMG_7789-rotated.jpeg?w=1200" padding="0px 0px 0px 0px" />
<!-- Cutline -->
<mj-text padding="0px 0px 0px 0px"><p class="cutline">Bargoers walk into Bread Bar in Silver Plume on Nov. 13. The bar quickly became standing room only as musicians played late into the night. (Provided by Stephanie Snyder)</p></mj-text><mj-text>

<p>There&#8217;s something strange about Silver Plume.</p>

<p>It&#8217;s practically a ghost town. It&#8217;s estimated that fewer than 200 people lived there in 2019. You may be more familiar with its neighbor Georgetown, one exit over on I-70.</p>

<p>Walking down Main Street, it feels like you&#8217;re about to run into the spirits of past silver miners. Old Western buildings still line the streets, housing the post office and town hall, as well as some folks&#8217; homes. Passersby can still coax a note or two from the out-of-tune piano out on the sidewalk.</p>

<p>But if you go on the right night, especially on a chilly one, and walk down that same street, you&#8217;ll find a particularly special building at the end of the road. Light will be spilling out of it, competing only against a flickering street lamp and the stars. Expansive windows will have become fogged with the condensation of all the bodies inside. And the loud noises of eager drinkers and heartbroken singers will welcome you in.</p>

<p>The building was a bakery in the 1800s. Now, it&#8217;s a bar that still declares &#8220;Bread&#8221; on its outside wall. It&#8217;s well named: <a target="_blank"  href="https://www.instagram.com/lillian.music/?hl=en">Bread Bar.</a> They understand the magic of simplicity — or perhaps it&#8217;s the magic of honesty. You&#8217;ll have to debate that with the friend you&#8217;re drinking with or with the person sitting next to you or with the musician as they grab a capo for their next song. Because whether it&#8217;s that or another topic, you&#8217;ll find yourself chatting with all three.</p>

<p>This past weekend it was standing room only, I was stumbling over feet and dogs just to get in line for the bar. A guitarist, <a target="_blank"  href="https://www.instagram.com/lillian.music/?hl=en">Lillian</a>, had just started her set and reminded people to whisper so others could hear her sing. The cocktails were stiff and delicious. And there was a beer fridge for those who preferred a trusty Coors Banquet.</p>

<p>You&#8217;ll stay longer than you expect — and that&#8217;s a good thing, because you might get lucky and be there when the bartenders are willing to keep the place open past close so the musicians can play more. And when you do eventually leave, you&#8217;ll find yourself with a buzz. But whether that&#8217;s from those stiff drinks or something else — something more innate to the place — will be unclear. I wish I could explain more, but I&#8217;m afraid I can&#8217;t. What can I say: It&#8217;s a mysterious place.</p>

