<h2><strong>In an essay from "Slow Arrow," a look to the heavens for beauty and meaning</strong></h2>

</mj-text><mj-image href="https://coloradosun.com/2021/11/21/sunlit-slow-arrow-kathryn-winograd/" src="https://lede-admin.coloradosun.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/15/2021/11/SlowArrowBookCover.jpeg?w=1200" padding="0px 0px 0px 0px" width="300px"/><mj-text>

<!-- Blockquote -->
<blockquote>&#8220;Sometimes, Leonard wakes me at two in the morning to watch the gibbous moon swallowed by Grouse Mountain. On winter nights, moonrise starts left of the butcher&#8217;s abandoned camper trailer where once our retired neighbor, vanished now, wiggled his ten blocky fingers at me and said, &#8216;Thirty years, and not a one lost.&#8217;&#8221;<br /><br /><span class="source">— From the essay &#8220;Skyglow&#8221;</span></blockquote>

<p><strong>EXCERPT:</strong> This opening paragraph from one of the last pieces in <strong>Kathryn Winograd&#8217;s</strong> collection <strong>&#8220;Slow Arrow: Unearthing the Frail Children&#8221;</strong> sets the mood for a poetic examination — though it&#8217;s not poetry, strictly speaking — of the night sky that both illuminates its mythic and scientific background and embraces it as a vehicle to explore the meaning of truth, beauty and family bonds. Winograd, whose volume was a Colorado Authors League award finalist, winds the reader through the celestial views from her family cabin in the Colorado mountains to her mother&#8217;s Denver apartment as she sets forth a poignant and beautiful discourse on light — and so much more.</p>

<p>&gt;&gt; <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2021/11/21/sunlit-slow-arrow-kathryn-winograd/?pico=clean"><strong>Read the entire SunLit excerpt.</strong></a></p>

<p><strong>THE SUNLIT INTERVIEW: </strong>When author and poet <strong>Kathryn Winograd</strong> talks about getting &#8220;a dope-slap from the universe,&#8221; she&#8217;s off and running with the story behind a collection of essays that draw heavily on her relationship with her mother, who moved to Denver from Ohio. As the two began a routine that took them all across the Colorado landscape, Winograd began writing essays that combine the unmistakable influence of her background in poetry with elements gleaned from the readings of a writer of creative nonfiction — the aforementioned &#8220;dope-slap.&#8221; Here&#8217;s a bit of the interview:</p>

<p><strong>Place this excerpt in context. How does it fit into the book as a whole? Why did you select it?</strong></p>

<p>&#8220;Skyglow&#8221; is one of the last essays in &#8220;Slow Arrow: Unearthing the Frail Children.&#8221;<em> </em>I wrote the essay after my mom had settled into Denver and we had started a companionable routine together. My mother was rapidly losing her sight at this point, and, at the same time, my husband and I were thick into our summer observation of the stars up at the cabin.</p>

<p>I had read statistics before on how few people in the world have the opportunity to see even the Milky Way at night. I began to see connections between that night blindness and my mother&#8217;s blindness. And then I asked my mother if she remembered a poem by <strong>John Keats</strong> about stars.</p>

<p>My mother, who had never shared with me her love for poetry, literally leapt up from her chair, sped to a tiny bookcase that housed the last of her books, and handed me &#8220;A Little Treasury of Poetry,&#8221; inscribed by her mother, my grandmother. Bookmarked and annotated years ago was Keats&#8217; poem, &#8220;Bright Star.&#8221; Thus began &#8220;Skyglow.&#8221;</p>

<p>&gt;&gt; <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2021/11/21/sunlit-kathryn-winograd-slow-arrow/?pico=clean"><strong>Read the entire interview with author Kathryn Winograd</strong></a><strong>.</strong></p>

